  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "To solve the limit \\(\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)\\), let's proceed step-by-step:\n\n1. **Rewrite the expression inside the limit:**\n   \\[\n   \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} (\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x)\n   \\]\n\n2. **Simplify the cube root term:**\n   Notice that as \\(x \\to \\infty\\), \\(x^3\\) will dominate \\(x^2\\). Let's factor out \\(x^3\\) from the cube root:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{x^3( \\frac{x^2}{x^3} - 1 )} = \\sqrt[3]{x^3( x^{-1} - 1 )} = x \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Rewrite the limit using the simplified cube root:**\n   \\[\n   \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( x \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + x \\right)\n   \\]\n\n4. **Factor out \\(x\\) from the expression:**\n   \\[\n   \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} x \\left( \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + 1 \\right)\n   \\]\n\n5. **Evaluate the limit inside the parentheses:**\n   As \\(x \\to \\infty\\), \\(\\frac{1}{x} \\to 0\\), so:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\to \\sqrt[3]{1} = 1\n   \\]\n   Therefore:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + 1 \\to 1 + 1 = 2\n   \\]\n\n6. **Combine the results:**\n   \\[\n   \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} x \\cdot 2 = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} 2x = \\infty\n   \\]\n\nThus, the limit is:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} (\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x) = \\infty\n\\]",
